    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/kGxQa.gif?s=256",
                "account_id": 453984,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 851273,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/851273/jon-lin",
                "reputation": 144351,
                "display_name": "Jon Lin"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 4,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1344485309,
            "creation_date": 1344484327,
            "body": "<p>If you know what the class is, you can use reflection:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public class Test\n{\n    int text01 = 2012;\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>And somewhere else, you can get that field's value by:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>String entrance = \"text01\";\nTest t = new Test();\n\nField f = t.getClass().getDeclaredField(entrance);\nSystem.out.println(\"value = \"+f.getInt(t));\n\n// you can even change the value:\nt.text01 = 2013;\nSystem.out.println(\"value = \"+f.getInt(t));\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>This will print out <code>2012<\/code>, then <code>2013<\/code>.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 11876542,
            "question_id": 11876475,
            "last_edit_date": 1344485309
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/80a0a1c7833b2f10bcd540bd7345c8d6?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1726740,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1581226,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1581226/qwerty",
                "reputation": 2512,
                "display_name": "qwerty",
                "accept_rate": 62
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1512625410,
            "creation_date": 1344485025,
            "body": "<p>The integer variable <code>text01<\/code> and the value <code>text01<\/code> stored in a string variable are two different things.<\/p>\n\n<p>It is not possible to get the value of a variable like this because both the <strong>int<\/strong> variable <code>text01<\/code> and the value stored in the <strong>string<\/strong> variable <code>text01<\/code> have nothing to do with each other.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Update:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>In case someone is looking for a simple approach to this using map is a good option. Just store variable names as keys and their values as key values<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>    Map&lt;String, Integer&gt; m = new HashMap&lt;String, Integer&gt;();\n\n\n    int text01=2012;\n    String entrance= \"text01\";\n\n    m.put(entrance, text01);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>to get the value<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>m.get(entrance);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 11876640,
            "question_id": 11876475,
            "last_edit_date": 1512625410
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/71093e2593d6cf16c4158849577153c4?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 1733142,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1586299,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1586299/michael",
                "reputation": 1012,
                "display_name": "Michael",
                "accept_rate": 50
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1344484351,
            "creation_date": 1344484351,
            "body": "<p>I think what you might want is something like this:\n<code>public Map values = new HashMap();\nvalues.add(\"text01\", 2012);<\/p>\n\n<p>System.out.println(values.get(\"text01\"));\n<\/code><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 11876544,
            "question_id": 11876475
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/583e4a7189a43d7223621ffe7fab6568?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 1494447,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1400737,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1400737/rogue-lad",
                "reputation": 2462,
                "display_name": "rogue lad",
                "accept_rate": 78
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1344485324,
            "creation_date": 1344485324,
            "body": "<blockquote>\n<p>int text01=2012；<\/p>\n<p>String entrance= &quot;text01&quot;;<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n<p>2012 and test01 are two different values that having different references.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 11876676,
            "question_id": 11876475,
            "last_edit_date": 1592644375
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a810cc8cecf3024d1dd3af6914e1e0ef?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 932972,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 962452,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/962452/kishor-sharma",
                "reputation": 599,
                "display_name": "Kishor Sharma",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1344489789,
            "creation_date": 1344489789,
            "body": "<p>You can use apache commons org.apache.commons.beanutils.PropertyUtils class for this.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>int text01 = 2012;\nString entrance = \"text01\";\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Just use : \nif your class object is Test test = new Test();<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Object value = PropertyUtils.getProperty(test, entrance);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 11877239,
            "question_id": 11876475
        }
